              "display_title": "Mid-Module Integrated Challenge",
              "learner_facing_content": "Mid-module integrated challenge for NATP Module 16. This single module challenge covers Objective 1, Objective 2, Objective 3, Objective 4 as much as possible.\n\nHigh-difficulty integrated challenge for NATP Module 16, covering O1, O2, O3, O4. You are midway through the module and must choose the safest, most complete CNA reasoning path across these topics: O1: Define key terminology; O2: Describe the five stages of the grieving process according to Dr. Kubler-Ross; O3: Describe approaches to meet common emotional and spiritual needs of terminally ill patients/residents and their families; O4: List the rights of the dying patient/resident. All choices include ideas that can sound reasonable; choose the one answer that satisfies every required safety condition: correct sequence, CNA scope, privacy, prompt reporting, objective documentation, and care-plan boundaries.\n\nA) Protect dignity first: explain the likely concern using the module terms, reassure the resident and family, then document what you observed.\nB) Complete the routine care step carefully, keep the resident comfortable, note the pattern, and report it later if the concern continues.\nC) Ask another CNA to confirm what you are seeing, compare it with prior-shift routine, then decide whether the nurse needs to be interrupted.\nD) Do less at first: pause the task, verify the care plan and current condition, protect privacy, report the changed or abnormal finding promptly, then document objective facts.\n\nSubmit a response, then review the debrief. Final assessments never reveal answer keys.",
